/*

    Extruded Offset Triangle Grid
    -----------------------------

    This is an extruded grid of packed rounded irregular triangles. The triangles
	are rendered using some common and not so common triangle geometry.

	I've been meaning to post an extruded triangle grid for some time, but I keep
    getting side tracked with other things -- Better late than never, I guess.
	The lack of examples pretty much everywhere tells me that people enjoy coding 
    up extruded triangles about as much as I do. :D In fact, I couldn't even track 
	down an irregular packed extruded triangle still image anywhere, let alone code, 
    but I'm sure it's out there. Either way, there's now a reference on Shadertoy, 
    and I've tried to make the process as painless as possible.

	In theory, rendering an extruded triangle grid is pretty simple: Render a
	regular square block grid, then chop each square block along the diagonal to
	produce triangles. However, in order to avoid artifacts, neighbors need to be 
    considered, which means four block renders per pass, or eight extruded triangles.
    On top of that, the aforementioned will only produce right angled isosceles 
    triangles, whereas most people will want nice regular equilateral ones. In order 
    to produce those, the rectangles need to be skewed (leant over to the right, in 
    this case) prior to subdivsion.

	Like most regular people, I don't enjoy implementing the skewing and unskewing
	process. I mean, I can do it, but I don't enjoy it. :) With that in mind, I 
    went to the trouble to clearly outline the process, so hopefully, it'll be easier 
    for anyone else who needs to do it.

    Anyway, the code's below. A lot of it is window dressing, so for anyone who
	would like to construct one of these, just look at the "map" function. For 
	anyone who was wondering, an offset rounded quadrilateral grid is possible using 
    a subset of this setup, and I have one ready to go.

    By the way, the comments are rushed, but I'll tidy them up in due course, and
	in case it isn't obvious, the example is a little GPU intensive, so I'll attempt
	to mitigate that as well. The most obvious thing I could do is bake the 2D
	face information into a buffer texture, then read from that, but for the purpose 
    of readability, I wanted to avoid that.


*/



// Offsetting the triangle coordinates. The look is a lot cleaner without it.
#define OFFSET_TRIS

// Skew the grid: In this case, we're just leaning the rectangles over to the 
// right a bit prior to the diagonal subdivision. I'm not sure who first noticed
// that it was a better way to create triangle grids, but I'm glad they did.
// Without skewing, you'll have subdivided right angled squares, which is fine,
// if that's the look you're going for.
#define SKEW_GRID

// Just the flat plane.
//#define FLAT_GRID


// Max ray distance.
#define FAR 20.


// Scene object ID to separate the mesh object from the terrain.
float objID;


// Standard 2D rotation formula.
mat2 rot2(in float a){ float c = cos(a), s = sin(a); return mat2(c, -s, s, c); }


// IQ's vec2 to float hash.
